Applying the Kirchhoff's Laws and the constitutive relationships for the elements, the general form of the algebraic system of equations modeling such a circuit is as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathrm{A}\mathbf{i}  = 0; \label{Tableau_1} \\
\mathrm{B}\mathbf{v} = 0; \label{Tableau_2} \\
\mathrm{M}\mathbf{v} + \mathrm{N}\mathbf{i} = 0, \label{Tableau_3}
\end{eqnarray}
being $\mathrm{A}$ the $(n-1)\times b$ \emph{incidence} matrix, $\mathrm{B}$ the $[b-(n-1)]\times b$ \emph{fundamental loop} matrix, while $\mathrm{M}$ and $\mathrm{N}$ are $b\times b$ \emph{coefficient} matrices specifying the constitutive relationship of all network elements. Further, $\mathbf{i}$ and $\mathbf{v}$ are $b\times 1$ vectors of currents and voltages, respectively. 


